text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!PracticeCategory]]%0a%0a!Indo-European Languages%0a%0a:Author: Mihir_D%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aHow come there are so many Indo-European languages (spoken by a lot of different people) and why are they so different? %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aAbout 46%25 of the world speaks a language in the Indo-European family, which consists of languages from Europe all the way to North India. I have also heard of Proto-Indo-European, the language thought to have been the common ancestor of all of these languages. The cognates between English, Spanish, and Latin, or between Hindi, Marathi, and Sanskrit seem obvious. But, I was really surprised to learn that there are still quite a few cognates between these European and Indian languages. %0a%0aColonialism spread English, Spanish, French, and Portuguese all over the world, but unlike the spread of these languages, the colonial languages did not change much compared to the originals. It is intriguing to me how the Indo-European language family became so popular and at the same time split up into so many varied forms. Many languages in the family use different writing systems, and I'm fairly sure the sounds used vary quite a bit as well. Europeans travelling to India must have found these similarities interesting to say the least.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexp